{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01EcjQziMZajZE5anzVVRyqs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me plan the two tasks:\n\n1. **DB Console at https://crdb-ui.example.com (TLS required)**:\n   - The CockroachDB DB Console runs on port 8080 in the `crdb-cluster-public` service\n   - I need to create a TLS secret (self-signed cert for `crdb-ui.example.com`) \n   - Create an Ingress resource with TLS using `nginx` ingress class\n   - The CockroachDB console itself uses HTTPS internally, so I need to handle the backend being HTTPS\n   - I'm realizing the DB Console is served over HTTPS by default when TLS is enabled, but I should verify whether CockroachDB is actually running in secure mode or insecure mode by checking the pod configuration.\n\nFor SQL traffic on port 26257, I need to set up a TCP service configmap entry pointing to the CockroachDB cluster, then patch the ingress-nginx controller with the appropriate arguments and expose that port on both the controller service and deployment. Let me check if the controller already has the `--tcp-services-configmap` argument configured.\n\nLooking at the deployment arguments, I don't see `--tcp-services-configmap` yet, so I'll need to add it. Now I need to check the CockroachDB pod to determine whether it's running in secure or insecure mode.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2291,"cache_read_input_tokens":29231,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2291},"output_tokens":19,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7de5e166-7b10-4a45-8a8d-8611f2287267","uuid":"39aba6e9-473e-47ee-a378-2fbc3737ba60","request_id":"req_011CcasPnqonVorVWbuw9cWo"}
